```graph
digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=box];

    Potentiometer [label="Potentiometer"];
    Buffer [label="Buffer Amplifier"];
    Scaling [label="Scaling Amplifier"];
    Filter [label="Band-stop Filter"];
    AntiAliasing [label="Anti-aliasing Filter"];
    DAQ [label="Data Acquisition (DAQ)"];

    Potentiometer -> Buffer;
    Buffer -> Scaling;
    Scaling -> Filter;
    Filter -> AntiAliasing;
    AntiAliasing -> DAQ;
}
```

```Explanations
Potentiometer: The potentiometer converts the mechanical angle of the pendulum into a corresponding electrical voltage. The center tap of the potentiometer is attached to the pendulum arm, while the other two terminals are connected to the -10 V and +10 V power supply.

Buffer Amplifier: This stage provides a high-impedance interface to the potentiometer, preventing loading effects and preserving the integrity of the signal. It also isolates the potentiometer from the rest of the signal conditioning stages.

Scaling Amplifier: Since the DAQ's maximum input voltage is +/- 7 V and the potentiometer provides a voltage range between -10 V and +10 V, this amplifier scales and shifts the voltage level to the required range for the DAQ, while also ensuring that the 90-degree position corresponds to 0 V.

Band-stop Filter: This filter attenuates unwanted frequencies around 50 and 60 Hz, which could be introduced from power line interference. A twin-T notch filter or an active band-stop filter can be used for this purpose.

Anti-aliasing Filter: An anti-aliasing filter is used to remove high-frequency components from the signal that are above the Nyquist frequency (half the sampling rate of the DAQ, which is 500 Hz in this case) to prevent aliasing when the signal is sampled by the DAQ.

DAQ: The Data Acquisition system samples the conditioned analog voltage signal at a rate of 1000 samples per second, converting it into a digital value for further processing and analysis.
```

